<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 9:15<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If638e9216b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I4b277990933c11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>9.</label.designator><headtext>Effect of Transfer: Proceedings in the Transferee Court</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94f9b709e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>9:15.</label.designator><headtext>Management of transferred cases—Lead and liaison counsel</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Panel has recognized the benefits of use of lead and liaison counsel. <eos/><bos/>Although it has not specifically recommended the use of lead and liaison counsel in specific cases, it has reiterated that the use of counsel in those roles would result in benefits of case management similar to those intended to be fostered by <cite.query w-src-number="0304914120" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I6ff5e0c06b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1">28 U.S.C.A. § 1407</cite.query>.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If638e9226b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>] Liaison counsel have been used to good effect by transferee courts in cases transferred by the Panel.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If638e9236b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If638e9216b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If638e9226b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See, e.g.,</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304914120" w-serial-number="1979117731" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="582" ID="I6ff62ee16b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1">In re Motion Picture Licensing Antitrust Litigation, 479 F. Supp. 581, 582 (J.P.M.L. 1979)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0304914120" w-serial-number="1977125577" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="1120" ID="I6ff62ee36b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1">In re Ascot Oils, Inc. Securities Litigation, 433 F. Supp. 1118, 1120 (J.P.M.L. 1977)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0304914120" w-serial-number="1976102719" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="246" ID="I6ff62ee56b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1">In re Air Crash Disaster at John F. Kennedy Intern. Airport on June 24, 1975, 407 F. Supp. 244, 246 (J.P.M.L. 1976)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0304914120" w-serial-number="1975107544" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="1406" ID="I6ff62ee76b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1">In re Radiation Incident at Washington, D. C. on April 5, 1974, 400 F. Supp. 1404, 1406 (J.P.M.L. 1975)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If638e9236b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See, e.g.,</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304914120" w-serial-number="1972107595" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="1385" ID="I6ff767616b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1">City of Detroit v. Grinnell Corp., 356 F. Supp. 1380, 1385 (S.D. N.Y. 1972)</cite.query>, <case.history>judgment aff&apos;d in part, rev&apos;d in part on other grounds</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0304914120" w-serial-number="1974110144" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000350" ID="I6ff767636b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1">495 F.2d 448 (2d Cir. 1974)</cite.query>; <ital>see generally</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304914120" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="LR" w-normalized-cite="35MLR15" w-pub-number="0003085" w-pinpoint-page="16" ID="I6ff767676b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1">John T. McDermott, <ital>The Transferee Judge—The Unsung Hero of Multidistrict Litigation</ital>, 35 <csc>Mont. L. Rev.</csc> 15, 16–19 (1974)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>MDLITMAN § 9:15<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
